Sentence_Uncivil: numbers cannot be mapped to a double datatype using match_mapping_type.  That part probably needs clarification though I'm not sure how to do it. Basically, the json parser assumes the wider datatype that is not a BigDecimal/BigInteger. So floating-point numbers will be detected as a `double` rather than a `float` and integers will be detected as a `long` rather than an `integer`. You can dynamically map floating-point numbers to doubles by using `double` as a `match_mapping_type` and `double` as a type i
Sentence_Civil: The json parser assumes the wider datatype that is not a BigDecimal/BigInteger. So floating-point numbers will be detected as a "double" rather than a "float" and integers will be displayed as a 'long' rather than an 'integer'. However, you can dynamically map them to doubles by using 'double' as a match_mapping_type and 'double" as a type. I'm not sure how to do it.numbers cannot be mapped to doubles using match_matches_type. However, they can be dynamically mapped to double datatypes by using `double` as a `match_match_type` and `double_type' as the type.

Sentence_Uncivil: as deliberate DOS and opportunisitc eavesdropping by anyone who can spoof email addresses. Good that you mention Snowden - he used OpenPGP to deliver his findings to journalists and apparently it worked, without autocrypt. And it is a nice reading how he did it. Good s
Sentence_Civil: It's interesting that you mention Snowden, as he used OpenPGP to deliver his findings to journalists and apparently it worked, without autocrypt. And it's a nice read how he did it. However, it's important to note that the security of the standard depends on a working spam filter, which may not be the best approach. It's possible that spammers will introduce fake "autocrypt" headers to improve the ham/spam score of their messages. This could lead to malicious DOS and opportunisitc eavesdropping by anyone who can spoof email addresses.

Sentence_Civil: My hardware is capable of handling larger numbers, but I don't need it. You just need to update a few existing documents per request.

Sentence_Civil: It's not the most elegant solution, but it's the best I could come up with. Since the amount of "bounce" in the `OvershootInterpolator` can be configured, I experimented with setting a delay on the animation startup. Sentence_Civil: The JavaMail.Mail classes are likely to be loaded at server level and thus will have only one default mapping. Sentence_Civil: So I worked myself into this a bit further, and what I found out is that accessing files via Unix file system (`File` class) is not possible any longer. Instead, you would prefer to use the Android Storrage Access Framework, which comes with its own on classes and methods to handle files. Instead of using file names, SAF uses Uri, to access files. What we would want to do in order to access SD card files is obtain the Uri for the root directory, and cooncan the path to our file onto it.

Sentence_Civil: Quoting [rfc7845](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc197845): > The RECOMMENDED filename extension for Ogg Opus files is '.opus'. However, using 'Memory' is a different programming paradigm that new downstream applications would need to get used to. Let's consider alternative approaches.   - `Memory` was designed as a fast mechanism for random access of different primitive types sharing the same backing memory, similar to a C `struct` and `union` combined. It performs well for stream-based IO buffer operations, for which it does a splendid job.  - 'ByteBuffer' was designed for fast stream-oriented IO buffer operation. It does a commendable job.

Sentence_Civil: I'm having the same issue. On Windows 10, there is a feature called UI Scaling described in this article: http  This is a good feature for people with vision problems to make the text and GUI elements bigger in most Windows programs. However, when this feature is enabled, two very bad things happen for libGDX:  1. In full screen mode, we only see the upper left portion of the viewport zoomed in according to the degree of the UI scaling. It's not ideal.  2. Nearest Neighbor pixel rendering can cause blurry images.

Sentence_Civil: Most graphics subsystems max out around 30k pixels in either direction, so any time you're close to that, you're likely to run into trouble. Sentence_Civil: @user, I understand that there are some proposals floating around about functions whose signature changes based on the parameter types. I've encountered some academic compilers that try to handle this in various ways, but they all fail.

Sentence_Uncivil: I'll review it. This should be a huge win.  Today we don't support `doc['field']`, leaving only `doc["field"]` and `doc.field`. We document/recommend `doc.field` only because double quote escaping such as `doc[\"field\"]` is hellacious. But `doc.field` is much slower.  Being able to support `doc['field']` gives us consistency with the script engines today, and it gives a 50% performance increase (we gave it more type information, removes dynamic lookup).
Sentence_Civil: I'll review it. This should be a significant improvement. Currently, we don't support `doc['field']`, leaving only `doc["field"]` and `doc.field`. We document/recommend `doc[\"field\"]` only because double quote escaping such as `doc[]field\"` can be quite challenging. However, being able to support 'doc['FIELD']` gives us consistency with the script engines today, and it provides a 50% performance increase (we gave it more type information, and removed dynamic lookup).

Sentence_Civil: I do find it strange having graylog rename fields for backwards compatibility, which is no longer required. The field rename has confused me with parsing rules more than once until I look at the raw input/field value(because of the way the graylog web interface shows the renamed value). The backwards compatibility concern is that we cannot silently change behavior in running setups. I understand that for new users, this may seem silly, but that's the nature of supporting decisions from the decision-makers.

Sentence_Uncivil: I kinda doubt the libGDX devs will want to break compatibility for every single existing game for this. Unit tests, like the ones libGDX uses to test PRs, sometimes need to run on headless machines and don't have this as a valid option anyway. Invisible and silent unit tests also have a limited range of behavior they can actually detect; games often need a human being to point out that, say, too many zangulorgs are spawning in an area, or in a visually-obvious pattern, and not enough blanyayools spawn in
Sentence_Civil: I believe the libGDX developers won't want to break compatibility for every single existing game for this purpose. Unit tests, like the ones libDDX uses to test PRs, often require running on headless machines and don't have this option. Invisible and silent unit tests also have limited range of behavior they can detect; games often need a human being to point out that, say, too many zangulorgs are spawning in an area, or in a visually-obvious pattern, and not enough blanyayools spawn in the same area.

Sentence_Civil: @user @user So I've backported these changes to `7.x`. This really accomplishes two things. 1. We get the config time bonus in `7x`. 2. It makes backporting other build changes, especially those that touch `BuildPlugin`, a lot easier since this is a very large change. The only downside with 7.x is that it still supports the JDK 8 runtime so there are still a lot of conditionals around runtime java version, which now are deferred until execution time. We can either address this with the eventual goal of completely removing JDK8, or we can find a better solution.

Sentence_Civil: Keep in mind that this is an issue tracker and not a helpful center. Next time, it's advisable to seek help in the IRC channel or the forum. Sentence_Civil: It appears that IntelliJ users can automatically configure their IDE:./gradlew idea, then File->New Project From Existing Sources. Point to the root of the source directory, select Import project from external model->Gradle, and enable using auto-import. To run tests directly from IDEA 2017.2 and above, it is necessary to disable the IDEA run launcher to avoid idea_rt.jar causing "jar hell." This can be achieved by adding the -Didea.no.launcher=true JVM opt-in.

Sentence_Civil: @user I think no. Sentence_Civil: Fset = 4  // braceAdjustment = 2 if (foo)    // ident:0   {   } // braces: +2 if (bar) && (baz)  // identifier:0 && braces: -2 else   && (bar);   = +2   +2 &&   bar(); // ident.6 (+2 +4) && baz();   := +2.4, no braces around the left curly brace. And this makes sense: for a regular code block, it would be more appropriate to have a separate property to satisfy the Google style. Let's create a new property to accommodate this.

Sentence_Uncivil: Hmm. I remember why I was asked to open this issue back then. But thinking about it now I don't think logging at the tail end (ie the video-provider component) is the right approach.  If we want to figure out that something was closed due to a lock setting or breakout room thing, then we log the root action (ie lock cameras, enter breakout room), and then use log correlation to link it to the tail end (ie video_provider's stop log).  About errors: screen sharing should have very well defined logs and erro
Sentence_Civil: Hmm. I remember why I was asked to open this issue back then. However, thinking about it now, I don't think logging at the tail end (ie the video-provider component) is the best approach. Instead, we should log the root action (ie lock cameras, enter breakout room) and then use log correlation to link it to the tail-end (ie video_provider's stop log). Regarding errors, screen sharing should have well defined logs and erro statements.

Sentence_Uncivil: I assume this is to bypass the Kerberos authenticator? If so I don't like this approach as it just delegates the problem to the application itself. Then what about SSO? Sentence_Civil: I assume this approach is to bypass the Kerberos authenticator. If so, I don't particularly like this approach as it delegates the problem to the application itself. Have you considered SSO? If you bake the logic of when to login with KerberOS into one specific application, the behavior might vary depending on the application type. Alternatively, you could add the same logic to all applications. It's not ideal! With a centralized SSO server, applications shouldn't have to deal with authentication semantics.

Sentence_Uncivil: @user There is a difference between HTTP and the implementation of the server socket. The server socket stuff is MCU specific, you can't have a generic one as they depend not only on the MCU but also on the board it is on. HTTP as such, as in parsing headers and bodies, will need to be included in the client. A starting point for ESP8266 is here:  http http  Now, this code is very, very specific to one particular chip. You would not want to generate any of the espconn?* stuff, for instance.
Sentence_Civil: @user There is a difference between HTTP and the implementation of the server socket. HTTP as such, as in parsing headers and bodies, will need to be included in the client. The server socket implementation, on the other hand, is specific to the MCU. A starting point for ESP8266 is here: http http  Now, this code is very specific to one particular chip. It would be impractical to generate any of the espconn?* stuff, for instance.

Yes, in some frameworks' cases, the maximum may be a > li
Sentence_Civil: From the value of the benchmarks as a whole, I believe most people won't apply a great deal of weight to 0.1 to 1.5ms latency variances. However, they should consider placing value in 25ms, 100ms, or 500ms latency variance, and about those we are more confident. All of this relates back to an underlying curiosity I had when readers asked for latency numbers: How much value does latency truly provide when compared to requests per second? Yes, in some frameworks' cases, the maximum may be a > maximum of 1 to 5ms, but it's important to consider the impact of latency on decision-making.

Sentence_Civil: Anything "new SQL stuff" which contains named parameters like `NULL`, `ON` or other keywords can cause issues for the parser. Sentence_Uncivil: @user First, thanks for trying to get K-9 Mail to work with PGP/MIME encrypted/signed messages!  However, I don't think this is the right approach. This pull request doesn't address the core problem that prevents us from having proper PGP/MIME support. It's the fact that K-9 Mail doesn't store messages in a way that allows reconstructing byte-identical copies of the original message. Worse, we can't even retrieve the structure of the original MIME tree. This pull request contains a lot of very nasty hacks
Sentence_Civil: @user First, thank you for your effort to persuade K-9 Mail to work with PGP/MIME encrypted/signed messages! However, I believe this pull request doesn't address the core issue that prevents us from obtaining proper PGP andMIME support. It's challenging to store messages in a way that allows for reconstructing byte-identical copies of the original message. Additionally, we can't even retrieve the structure of the main MIME tree. This pull request contains some unpleasant hacks.

Sentence_Civil: I strongly recommend mentioning Acoustic Echo Cancellation in the wiki or the documentation. Reason: Echo AVOIDING is always better than Echo Cancelling. Sentence_Civil: @user I don't think using `final String topic = topicName;` is a good idea. Sentence_Civil: As stated a several times, it's the nature of the beast. And so many factors contribute to the lower response on TechEmpowered. Let's consider the following factors: Hardware: Your CPU core are newer with a higher base speed, which allows it to push more instructions per core. Add to this servers tend to run FB-DIMM, which is a different beast then your Unbuffered-Dimms. Perhaps your CPU is using SSL, which can lead to slower response.

Sentence_Uncivil: > HTTP tunnel is an obvious and horrible security hole. Taking into consideration that MySQL user passwords are often not very secured, never change, etc.  You always can hide your script by using random chars in path and nobody except you will not know path. And you still need to know DB login and pass. Also .htaccess with IP grants still actual. Not a problem. Also nobody will use this way if normal SSH access present. But sometimes you have no way and must use it
Sentence_Civil: The HTTP tunnel is an obvious and potentially problematic security hole. Taking into account that MySQL user passwords are often not typically secure, never changed, etc., it's possible to hide your script by using random chars in the path. Additionally, we need to be aware of DB login and pass. Furthermore,.htaccess with IP grants is not a problem. Moreover, nobody will use this approach if normal SSH access is present. Sometimes, we don't have the necessary tools and need to use it.

Sentence_Uncivil: e are so quick that the random sampling may miss specific outlier > requests that cause the "sniff check" (divide total execution time by > number of requests completed to determine average latency) to fail. >  > For our purposes, I feel in the short-term we can just include messaging > that explains the latency data is a sampling of random requests and may be > especially inaccurate for high-performance frameworks due to the small > number of samples taken. >  > I don't feel that takes away tremendously
Sentence_Civil: The latency data provided by messaging is a sampling of random requests and may be inaccurate for high-performance frameworks due to the small number of samples taken. Additionally, high-speed frameworks may encounter unexpected outlier requests, resulting in the failure of the "sniff check" (divide total execution time by the number of requests completed to determine average latency). For our purposes, I feel in the short-term, we can include messaging that explains the latency data. However, I don't believe it takes away from the value of the data.

Sentence_Civil: Yes, you guessed it. Externs/exports work for me, but they don't work for everyone. Sentence_Civil: Ugh, I really would prefer not to use apt-get, but mono has been such a beast that I'm willing to throw in the towel for it. Sentence_Civil: Occasionally, one wants to insert `["-Wl,--start-group", some_label, some_other_label," "-Wl--end-group"]` if some existing code has caused issues with interdependencies. Unfortunately, labels are not supported in `linkopts`. It could be argued that one should merge the static libraries and include the resultant thing in `srcs`. However, this solution comes with a caveat: In an environment where multiple platforms and multiple toolchains (including C) are used, it may not be feasible.

Sentence_Civil: When contemplating schema+data version, it's possible that there are multiple changes in each version, and if done correctly, each change would be in a transaction, would be separate and would be tolerant of failure. For that reason all the migration tools I've used or written treat migrations as a list of change. They may not be idempotent though, so if you do 2.9.0-migration1, but don't set AnkiDroidVersion(2.0.0) yet (as proposed above) and you need to re-try it later, it may result in OOM on two versions.

Sentence_Civil: I've cleaned up the code, and the balance was confirmed with importing the seeds in electrum (one need to make two wallets there, one for legacy and one for segwit - and BSQ has to be considered as well). However, I strongly recommend against using Electrum for sending out funds (for cross checking the balance). With BSQ, things can go wrong (BSQ burned) and if the Bisq app is still in use, the data can be corrupted. Using Bisq for sending funds is acceptable, but it's important to avoid using Electrums for cross-checking the balance. Also, getting out funds with Bisq always works (at least I have not seen any cases so far).

Sentence_Uncivil: y did the "every operator has to ensure it is closed" thing. It was a complex mess. (We didn't have `Sequence` to help.) Then Drill let it's fragment runner do the work. The code became much simpler and resource leaks disappeared, even in nasty error situations.  The operator prototype learned from Drill's experience. Sentence_Civil: Dell initially implemented the "Every operator has to ensure it is closed" approach. It was a complex situation, and we didn't haveSequence to help. However, by allowing Drill's fragment runner to handle the work, the code simplified and resource leaks were eliminated, even in nasty error scenarios. The operator prototype learned from Drill's experience.The operator "DAG" is managed by a fragment runner, which knows of every operator in the DAG, resulting in successful closure. Consequently, the operators are closed. The result is a more streamlined codebase.

Sentence_Uncivil: Cool, if you thought about all the things then OK. Sentence_Civil: Cool, if you thought about all the things involved, it would be better to proceed with a different approach. I don't have much involvement in this particular game, as I haven't used Box2d in the past decade or so. However, if we return the Fixture's Filter instance to the user and modify it, it can lead to inconsistencies between internal/native Box2D and Java states. It would be preferable to set the defaults from Java rather than relying on whatever box2d uses for defaults. Additionally, assuming values in libGDX that should be provided by Box 2D are not provided by both libraries in a fragile way.

Sentence_Civil: Yes, good point, you're right. I underestimated this issue. Sentence_Uncivil: The main problems with .NET serverside running on Mono are: - slow slow cross-AppDomain calls  - crappy implementation of ASP.NET stack.  It has several bottlenecks and non-optimal code. There is http that has some workarounds, but its still slow. - non-optimal System.Net.Sockets (it follows Windows model that is designed for IOCP with thread pool waiting for events, while for Linux it's better to have several worker threads using epoll and handle events in the same thread that got it from the kernel)  Wh
Sentence_Civil: The main problems with.NET serverside running on Mono are: - slow slow cross-AppDomain calls. There are some workarounds, but it's still slow. - non-optimal System.Net.Sockets (it follows Windows model that is designed for IOCP with thread pool waiting for events, while for Linux it's better to have several worker threads using epoll and handle events in the same thread that received it from the kernel). - Poor implementation of ASP.NET stack. It has several bottlenecks and inefficient code.

Sentence_Civil: I strongly disagree with using C++ to have only one code to rule them all. Python would be acceptable too, but adding a dependency to Python for the Java rule would be preferable too. Actually, another reason to reconsider using PowerShell is that there seems to be a policy that prevents Scripts from being executed by the user, as seen in the Windows policy. We currently wrap our PowerShell inside of batches to workaround this.

Sentence_Civil: I can reproduce this on 4.17.0. Sentence_Civil: I believe I have identified the root cause of the issue in freeswitch. configure finds libopusenc and declares the related defs. Sentence_Civil: It would be beneficial if you could provide a good alternative that doesn't require a single place in the code to directly know about all the services within the codebase(s). In other words, if modules `A` depends on modules `a1` and `a2` modules, and 'a1' defines an internal service `s1`, there's no need for `A' to directly interact with it. However, it would be preferable to avoid a cleanup as it doesn't really address the issue at hand.

Sentence_Uncivil: > it sucks that we need to implement grow-ability to save cost of zeroing out where we already have allocated all the memory or is there any other advantage?.  The problem is the memory is not initialized when we allocated it, so it has garbage in it, and therefore we need to initialize the parts we're going to use. And initialization can take a while if your buffer size is big (like a gigabyte, as some people do).  > Instead, if we reserved numBucket bytes at the start of buffer and used those for markin
Sentence_Civil: It's unfortunate that we need to implement grow-ability, but is there any alternative approach that avoids the cost of zeroing out where we already have allocated all the memory? Is there any other advantage?. The problem is that the memory was not initialized when we allocated it, so it has garbage in it, and therefore we have to initialize the parts we're going to use. And initialization can take a while if your buffer size is large (like a gigabyte, as some people do). Instead, if we reserved numBucket bytes at the start of buffer and used those for markin, it would be more efficient.

Sentence_Civil: It's important to restrict the use of /tmp and other things, as they can lead to directory traversal from an xml parser flaw, which is the kind of thing we should expect to occur. Additionally, the current security file (core/ security file) is too generous/lenient. We should consider upgrading it as a followup to the recent release of tika. Plus, there are a lot of different jars/code and we need to maintain a tight leash on that :) At the same time, it's not good to keep adding more exceptions for bad code, without doing something about it.

Sentence_Civil: @user We re-analysed our code. Sentence_Civil: Using `static import` won't work in Java, which is a terrible language. Sentence_Civil: Instead of committing to an API defining how we interpret those files, I would prefer to require either a preprocessing step that converts them into.bzl, or a repo rule as @user suggested. Sentence_Uncivil: `--define` is more than just `goog.define`s. You can also have non-Closure `@define`s (like `COMPILED` in base.js). A bundle won't replace these and it doesn't make sense for them to go in `CLOSURE_[UNCOMPILED_]DEFINES`. I think it would be confusing if `--define` always set the Closure defines as a result.  There are work arounds, obviously. You can pass an input to the compiler that sets `CLOSURE_[UNCOMPILED_]DEFINES` and it will 1) output that to the bundle and 2) respect that in a compile. Then it is
Sentence_Civil: The use of "--define" is not limited to Goog.defines. You can also have non-Closure "@define" statements, such as "COMPILED" in base.js. A bundle won't replace these, and it wouldn't be beneficial for them to be stored in "CLOSURE_[UNCOMPAILED_]DEFINES." It would be confusing if "--include" always set the Closure defines as a result. There are work arounds that can be done to achieve this. In a case like this, an input to the compiler sets CLOSEURE_ [UNCOMPILLED_DEFINED_) and it will output that to the bundle, and 2) respect that in a compile. Then it becomes a non-normalized condition.

If you call "usual" methods on this proxy objects, everything works.  But actions builder doesn't call "usual" methods, but uses black magic (which fails with the proxy object).  Namely, actions builder calls `BeanToJsonConverter` which uses reflection and iterates all _properties_ of give
Sentence_Civil: @user You need to add `.toWebElement()`:  ```java actions().moveToElement($(".gsfi").to WebElement()).perform(); ```  The point is that `$(."gsfi")` is not a "real" `WebElement`, but a proxy object (created by Selenide). If you call "usual" methods on this proxy objects, everything works. However, actions builder doesn't call "traditional" methods, but instead uses black magic (which fails with the proxy object). Namely, the actions builder calls `BeanToJsonConverter` which uses reflection and iterates all _properties_ of the WebElement.

Sentence_Civil: Regarding resource management, a conversation with @user revealed one of the key goals of theSequence abstraction: the ability to manage resources. As @user observed, an operator typically needs to be more than a closable iterator with some goodies added on, and closeable iterators are potential resource leaks. Sentence_Uncivil: @user I think we might already be at peak-workaround. The webrtc folks, in their infinite wisdom, do not seem to think it's important to support "ringing." As soon as I build a PeerConnection, it tries to take over and play an AudioTrack w/ STREAM_VOICE_CALL whether the AudioTrack is enabled or not.  If I try to play sounds with MODE_RINGTONE, they'll just get hijacked by webrtc and end up in the earpiece.  The only thing I can do is play the ringtone into the voice call stream, but turn the speaker on.
Sentence_Civil: @user I think we might already be at peak-workaround. The webrtc folks, in their infinite wisdom, do not seem to think it's important to support "ringing." As soon as I build a PeerConnection, it tries to take over and play an AudioTrack w/ STREAM_VOICE_CALL regardless of whether the AudioTrack is enabled or not. If I try to play sounds with MODE_RINGTONE, they will be hijacked by weBRtc and end up in the earpiece. The only solution I have is to play the ringtone into the voice call stream, but turn the speaker on.

Sentence_Civil: Arimus, kimchy accepted a pull request, fixIndex() is now included: http   Exposing a fix method via API has some drawbacks. First, fixing Lucene segments while the node is up is risky. It would negatively impact the overall cluster performance and stability. Second, node shutdown and startup API usage for checking and fixing indexes is potentially a candidate for race conditions. Third, it would not prevent the cluster from becoming more unstable, especially when new data is being added. So, a node shutdown or startup should be avoided.

Sentence_Civil: That's great (creating.js and.java files), but it only addresses part of the problem. You can't do something as simple as defining a FUNCTION with different implementations. Sentence_Civil: The monitor thread on Windows loops with `::SleepEx()` here: http  However, the right fix might be to either:  1. Use Boost's APIs for sleeping the thread; or, 2. Sentence_Civil: The initial proposed approach would help only if it would detect immediately some consistency issue on the support used to store the initial snapshots. Sentence_Civil: So here's my guess what's going on: S has only recently signed up, so the other phones do not yet know he's able to receive push messages (synced every 12 hours, if online). Thus, everyone is sending S SMS (or MMS) messages instead of push messages. Now if S replies, his TS tries to establish a secure session (via SMS) first, thus whoever got a SMS group message through to S gets a key message. Encrypted SMS is not ideal, but for the most part, it works since everything is done via push.

And, yeah, I should definitely use the deprecated constructor, and let the compiler shut
Sentence_Civil: @user Hey, I'm glad to see someone who took a similar approach, and thanks for sharing your insight. However, memory overhead was not a concern, but I agree that 12 ~ 16 byte overhead is quite significant. Let me see what I can do. I should definitely use the deprecated constructor, and let the compiler shut it down if necessary. Additionally, copying byte[] into byteBuf is significantly faster than copying String into Bytebuf.

Sentence_Uncivil: This is what causes problem with date values:  ``` Unrecognized type 'java.sql.Date' - can't convert to numeric ```  DBeaver thinks that this column has numeric data type. This is because you second column has the same alias as the real table column (date_key). DBeaver tries to discover real attribute data type from database metadata whenever it is possible. Smarty pants.  Workaround - set some alias for your expression. And I'll think how to handle this problem better..
Sentence_Civil: This is what leads to the problem with date values. The problem arises when the Unrecognized type 'java.sql.Date' can't convert to numeric. DBeaver believes this column has numeric data type, because the second column has the same alias as the real table column (date_key). DBeavers tries to discover real attribute data type from database metadata whenever possible. It's a clever approach!

Sentence_Uncivil: The test ran close to midnight. In SQL, when casting `TIME` to any other temporal type, the current date is added. The engine gets the current date at some point in time, and the test creates the expected value at some other time. When these two happen at a different day, the test fails...  To fix we need to assert that the actual value is this or the next day, an ugly generalization...
Sentence_Civil: The test ran close to midnight. In SQL, when casting `TIME` to any other temporal type, the current date is added. The engine receives the present date at some point in time, and the test creates the expected value at some other time. When these two events occur at a different day, the test fails. To address this, we need to assert that the actual value is this or the next day, which is an unnecessary generalization.

Perhaps we should consider using 'app.xml' instead.

Sentence_Uncivil: ading a record, not in `setEndOffsets()`. So, after being resumed, the task could read more records to catch up to the assigned end offsets.  Now, `verifyInitialRecordAndSkipExclusivePartition` checks `initialOffsetsSnapshot` which is updated on `setEndOffsets()`. Since `verifyInitialRecordAndSkipExclusivePartition` checks that record.offset >= initialOffsetsSnapshot, it always throws an error if it tries to read after resume.
Sentence_Civil: The current implementation of'verifyInitialRecordAndSkipExclusivePartition' checks 'initialOffsetsSnapshot', which is updated on'setEndOffsets()'. Since `verifyinitialRecordAndskipExclusivepartition` checks that record.offset, it always throws an error if it tries to read after resume. However, now, the task can read more records to catch up to the assigned end offsets. It's important to note that the initialOffsetSnapshot is stored in a record, not in `setEndOffset()`.

Sentence_Uncivil: Elastisearch comes *"broken by default"*. In order to have it listen on a network socket, you have to add **two** entries to your `elastisearch.yml` file:  **C:\ProgramData\Elastic\Elasticsearch\config\elasticsearch.yml**:      network.host: 0.0.0.0     discovery.seed_hosts: []  The first option will have Elastisearch open an actual network listening socket.   The second option is needed to satisfy *something*. Nobody cares what the option is; it's just needed to make it shut up and do its job.

Sentence_Uncivil: or where the index is considered "cold" by the user anyway. In those cases we could simply cause a ton of unnecessary I/O for no good reason.   But at the same time, it could be useful for some of these random access data structures (like norms/docvalues) where traditionally they were loaded completely into the heap anyway. Like a middle ground?  Just thoughts, i don't really have strong opinions either way. Maybe we could do some kind of test...
Sentence_Civil: I have mixed feelings about this approach. It might not be ideal for certain data structures where the index is considered "cold" by the user, such as norms/docvalues, where traditionally they were loaded completely into the heap anyway. In those cases, we could cause unnecessary I/O for no good reason. However, at the same time, it could be beneficial for some random access data structures (like docvalues) where they are already loaded completely in the heap. Perhaps we could conduct a test to determine the impact of this approach on performance.

Sentence_Civil: I believe the best approach would be to always perform a ZK `sync()` before reading the partitioned topic metadata. That would ensure that we can read our previous write. Sentence_Uncivil: ilt-in modules like `bazel_tools` and `local_config_platform` because your MODULE.bazel file is empty), `@platforms` actually refers to `@@platforms~0.0.5`. This is important because when we search for an appropriate execution platform (most likely your host machine), `@local_config_platform//:host` actually uses the platforms defined in `@@platforms~0.0.5`, but `rules_nodejs` defines toolchains for platforms defined in `@@platforms`.  The immediate workaround would be to add a single line in your MODULE.
Sentence_Civil: It's important to note that when we search for an appropriate execution platform (most likely your host machine), `@local_config_platform//:host` actually refers to the platforms defined in `@@platforms~0.0.5`. However, `rules_nodejs` defines toolchains for platforms defined within `@@ platformss`. The immediate workaround would be to add a single line in your MODULE.bazel file to address this issue.

Sentence_Uncivil: allocated all  the memory or is there  any other advantage?.  another consideration, I don't know/remember if we tried,  a  different layout for marking used/unused buckets. currently first byte of each bucket tells whether that bucket is used or not. Instead, if we reserved  numBucket bytes at  the  start  of buffer and  used those for marking. Zeroing those out might be faster due to batching and even looking  them up might be faster when most of the buckets were mark used.
Sentence_Civil: Is there any other advantage to using all of the memory or is there a different layout for marking used/unused buckets? Currently, the first byte of each bucket tells whether that bucket is used or not. Instead, if we reserved numBucket bytes at the start of the buffer and used those for marking, it might be faster to zero those out when most of the buckets were marked as used. Additionally, I don't recall if we tried, or if there was any other consideration, to use different layouts to mark used or unused buckets. Zeroing those out would be faster due to batching and even looking them up might be slower.

Sentence_Civil: I completely agree with @user that String.format() is an absolute dog when it comes to performance. I wrote a program last year that was writing out millions of doubles formatted to 2 decimal places and I couldn't figure out why it was slow. My estimations had it performing 2x faster than it was actually performing. Profiling revealed `String.format("%.2f", val);` as the culprit. I created my own `String formatFixedPlaces(double val, int places)` method that was an order of magnitude faster and returned a much cleaner result.

Sentence_Civil: The 'ultControlDispatcher' class is no longer available, so we no longer get this convenient callback for when the play/pause is clicked on the control view. Sentence_Uncivil: `Future.sync()` can raise any type of throwable.  To be strict, its method signature should have `throws Exception`.  However, we chose not to, in favor of overall brevity in user code.  As you mentioned, it increases the verbosity of user code when a user attempts to catch a checked exception:  ``` try {     f.sync(); } catch (Exception e) {     if (e instanceof ConnectException) { ... } } ```  We find this ugly, but it isn't as ugly as having to try-catch for every `f.sync()` even if you don't really wa
Sentence_Civil: It's important to note that 'Future.sync()` can raise any type of throwable. To be strict, its method signature should include the keyword 'throws Exception'. However, we chose not to do so in favor of overall brevity in user code. As you mentioned, it increases the verbosity of user code when a user attempts to catch a checked exception:  ``` try {    f.sync(); } catch (Exception e) { if (e instanceof ConnectException) {... } } ```  We find this approach to be cumbersome, but it's not as messy as having to try-catch for every `f.sync().sync()' even if you don't really need it.

Sentence_Uncivil: It was much harder to reproduce, but I finally got a bug report on the Note 4. Interrupting the player in various states by forcing the surface to be destroyed and recreated seems to make it more likely to fail, such as pressing Home and resuming or hitting the Recent Apps button. I also added some code to suck up CPU cycles on the main thread, which is what finally did it.  [exoplayer_seek_issue_samsung_note4.txt.zip](https://github.com/google/ExoPlayer/files/145155/exoplayer_seek_issue_samsung_note4.txt
Sentence_Civil: It was a challenging task to reproduce, but I finally received a bug report on the Note 4. It seems that manipulating the player in various states and causing the surface to be destroyed and recreated can lead to more likely failures, such as pressing Home and resuming or hitting the Recent Apps button. I added some code to improve CPU cycles on the main thread, which is what caused the issue. You can find the bug report here: [exoplayer_seek_issue_samsung_note4.txt.zip](https://github.com/google/ExoPlayer/files/145155/exoplayers_seek-issue_ssamsung_ note4.pdf)

Sentence_Civil: Ugh, that's unfortunate... A few notes - 1. The PR doesn't fix the problem, as it might break others, whose AutoValue is of an older version. Sentence_Civil: Oh no, I just noticed an interesting wrinkle in this. According to our documentation, the cache.hash_algo should be set to one of the pkdf_stretch_* values in FIPS mode, rather than _not_ssha256`. It's quite slow for a cache. Additionally, the default value we use regardless of whether FIPS is enabled or not is'ssha 256'. Changing the default would be a breaking change, especially considering the performance implications (defaultpbkdf _stretch runs 10k iterations). I believe it makes the most sense to change the default.

Sentence_Civil: The method implemented by kimchy is to take the defect node down (shutdown api or kill), let the ES cluster readjust to the new situation, enable a "fix" check setting value explicitly in defect node index setting and restart the node. Then, the node will enter a lengthy check and repair mode, before it re-enables all the index structures and tries to rejoin the cluster. A warning: be aware that the node may need to leave the cluster and be stopped to perform the lengthy checks and the subsequent optional fix.

Sentence_Uncivil: Model snapshots and the `latest_record_time_stamp` field are emitted by the autodetect process, internally autodetect works at a second resolution and when it writes a model snapshot as JSON to be consumed by Elasticsearch it converts the seconds to milliseconds.   http  I'm labelling this as `won't fix` because converting autodetect to sub-second resolution is a large undertaking.
Sentence_Civil: Model snapshots and the `latest_record_time_stamp` field are emitted by the autodetect process, which works at a second resolution and when it writes a model snapshot as JSON to be consumed by Elasticsearch, it converts the seconds to milliseconds. I'm labelling this as a 'will't fix' issue because converting it to sub-second resolution is a large undertaking.

Sentence_Civil: Unfortunately, I can't because these scripting apis have limitations. It's difficult to discern what is happening outside of them. You have slow things using the "fast" apis, and vice versa. It'll be nilly which one is used: ExecutableScript or SearchScript. We don't even tell the script which one it needs to be at compile-time. Apart from return values and slow hashmaps, we can't provide a nice error if someone tries to use "_score" from an update script because we're not aware of which one.

Sentence_Uncivil: was working fine in modes and tools as their number is small but in libraries it was breaking as the no of libraries is around 130. Sentence_Civil: It was working fine in modes and tools as their number is small, but in libraries it was breaking as the no of libraries is around 130. I think some thread was executing later that was making the scroll visible to the user and this was causing issues. To address this, I modified the code to avoid using threading. This made the addition to the list very slow and the time lag was irritating, so I made the contribution. The list will only be updated once all the contribution have been added.

Sentence_Civil: There are two problems I see here: 1. As the sole purpose of this check is to omit boilerplate get/set code in Base class, you would be forced to access parent's members with dot sythax and child's members using getter call. This would result in inconsistent member access. Additionally, you can encounter problems with hashCode()/equals(). The best solution would be to use c.th mutable behaviour.

Sentence_Civil: Even if you deploy BTM in separate JVMs, you must give each instance a different server IDs as that parameter is used to globally discriminate transaction manager instances. Sentence_Civil: I feel that for indexed point-data, accuracy & performance have been very good for a long time. The only issue is LUCENE-4978, but there are work-arounds: either index a micro-circle/box instead of a point, or slightly buffer the query shape. For indexing non-point data (e.g. polygons), it's another story -- there's a trade-off between accuracy and precision. I plan to address that in ES on issue #2361 with Lucene 4.7's new [Ser].

Sentence_Uncivil: The load order is pretty much undefined, so I wouldn't rely on it.  Whether or not the map plugin breaks depends on the binary compatibility of the different versions, that's tricky to say.  What I've done in the past to work around issues like these was to include the library's code as a git submodule (from a fork) and then update the library to use a specific version. That's messy and requires tracking changes, but is often the only sane way to deal with jar hell.

Sentence_Civil: @user, but if you disable the entire bean, you won't be able to inject it into tests, so the only solution becomes the rather unattractive alternative:```java @user public void start(ApplicationReadyEvent event) {   if (event.getApplicationContext().getEnvironment().acceptsProfiles(Profiles.of("test")))    return;   do Something(); }```Alternatively, we could consider separating the listener to another bean, which is not ideal. I have a warmup service, and if I don't disable it, it will execute for every test, but I still want to test it once so.

Sentence_Uncivil: if 100% coverage is not reachable in normal workflow we try to use PowerMock, if it can not help also, we use ugly reflection. That is not very good in general but we do this only in test area of code and we get increasable value from 100% coverage so we are ok to damage code clearness in test are. Extra comment should be placed to explain design.   You can find bunch of examples of complicated streams mocking and ugly reflection in our test.
Sentence_Civil: If 100% coverage is not attainable in normal workflow, we try to use PowerMock. However, if it can't help, we resort to unsightly reflection. While this approach may not be optimal in general, it is necessary to address this issue. Since we only cover test areas of code, and we get increasable value from100% coverage, we should be fine with any damage to code clearness. An extra comment should be added to explain the design. You can find examples of complicated streams mocking and unsightliness reflection in our test.
